Project: Ford GoBike Data Analysis¶

by Chisom Ibezim¶

Introduction¶

The Ford GoBike system is an integral part of the Bay Areas transportation network. With more than 300 stations and 3,000 bikes on the ground across San Francisco, San Jose, Berkeley, Oakland and Emeryville, the system has generated over two million rides since launching in June 2017.MTC (2022)

This dataset contain information about trips taken using the Ford GoBike for a given period in the San Francisco Bay Area. Some useful features contained in this dataset include trip duration, start time, end time, start station_id, end station id, bike user id, etc. I will be exploring variables and relationships to answer some questions.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset contains 183412 fordgobike journeys with 16 specifications (duration sec, start time, end time, start station id, start station name, start station latitude, start station longitude, bike id, user type, member birth year, member gender, bike share for all trip). Nine of the sixteen specifications are numerical, two are datetime, four are object type, and one is boolean type.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I am particularly interested in determining how trip duration is affected by other features in the dataset.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I anticipate that trip time will be significantly dependent on the distance between start and end stations, and the age of the rider; I also believe that user type and gender should have an impact on journey time.

This implies that such members are overaged and don't have the strength and capacity to ride a bike. Since we have enough records to work with, such entries will be dropped, and the minimum birth year will be set to 1940.

In [9]:
# Defining a function for identifying upper and lower limits
def outlier(i):
    '''returns the upper and lower limits of a quantitative variable'''
    q3=i.quantile(.75)
    q2=i.quantile(.25)
    IQR=q3-q2
    u=i.quantile(.75)+1.5*IQR
    l=i.quantile(.25)-1.5*IQR
    output = print(f"The upper limit is: {u}\nThe lower limit is: {l}")
    return output
outlier(df_c['duration_sec'])

The upper limit is: 1488.0
The lower limit is: -376.0

#Creating a new variable Distance_in_KM
from math import sin, cos, asin, sqrt
def get_distance(row, R = 6371): #to be expressed in kilometer
    dlon = row[1]['end_station_longitude'] - row[1]['start_station_longitude']
    dlat = row[1]['end_station_latitude'] - row[1]['start_station_latitude']

    a = ((sin(dlat/2))**2 + cos(row[1]['start_station_latitude']) * cos(row[1]['end_station_latitude']) * (sin(dlon/2))**2)
    c = 2 * asin(sqrt(a))
    return R * c

df_c['distance_in_km'] = [get_distance(row) for row in df_c.iterrows()]

Conclusions¶

This exploration has exposed us to the exciting properties of the Ford GoBike Trip data. We saw that most Males used bikes more than other gender categories in the exploration, and that over 85% of bike users are subscribers. The quantitative variables are positively skewed leaving us with no incentive to use advance statistical techniques like multiple linear regression, even when trip time and distance covered has high correlation.
